    "updated_at": "2024-11-06T21:14:32Z",
    "body": "@mibmo So I'm just doing worktrees as subdirectories in my bare repo. But when I create my bare repo, I pass path with `/.git` appended like this...\r\n\r\n```\r\ngit clone --bare https://github.com/some/project.git project/.git\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis cleans up the top level of my bare repo directory...\r\n\r\n![CleanShot 2024-11-06 at 16 10 39](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6793365a-25ad-4b08-bb43-4c9dc0a8f61f)\r\n\r\nBut git recognizes the `.git` folder convention for storing config/refs/etc.\r\n\r\n![CleanShot 2024-11-06 at 16 11 23](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d83fe470-9b82-495d-a0c7-3ae8a9e146a0)\r\n\r\nThe confusing thing about seeing that `5.x` branch module in starship at top level is, I technically don't have branch checked out at the top level of my repo because it's a bare repo. `5.x` happens to be our default branch on github, so rev-parse HEAD points to that, but that module info is useless to me at the bare repo root.\r\n\r\nI'd almost prefer adding my own custom starship module that shows something different when at bare repo root, but first I have to figure out how to conditionally disable `git_branch` and `git_status` modules at bare root level.\r\n\r\nAnyway, hope the info helps!",
    "author_association": "NONE",
